Hi everyone! @treaganwhite here! Listen up please! 
I have NO DOUBT that the way @kimcankickit treated her body, through diet and exercise, kept her here in this world for years beyond what was predicted after her initial diagnosis. Those of you who followed her then, or have now searched her previous posts, know how she would plead with us all to take care of our bodies. Above all, she encouraged us to MOVE. Whatever that means to you, just move. Appreciate the miracle that is your body! Savor the moments when you are out of breath during vigorous exercise! Don’t take for granted the fact that you can walk around with ease, that you can ride a bike, or even that you can lift and play with your children. LOVE your body! If the time comes when you can no longer move with relative ease, you will want nothing more than to leap from your couch, bed, or chair to engage in ANY type of bodily movement. Don’t let that happen! Move your body now! Thank you Kim, for pushing us to do this. Thank you Jane ( @olsenjs ) for reminding us and carrying on with Kim’s message!  We love you both!

#kimcankickit #idoitforkim #doitforkim #movelikekim #loveyourbody #getupandmove #moveyourbody

For the last several years, she spent this season raising money and contacting sponsors to help support young mothers facing a recent cancer diagnosis.
Please help us continue this noble pursuit! We need you to nominate young moms and we need donations.  I’ll tell you how in the story highlights, go take a look.
Also, go follow @liftedby_angels to see how your donations are being used this year.

I am feeling so much gratitude today! I can’t believe how much love and support we have felt over the past few weeks from friends, family, neighbors and complete strangers. We have suffered a blow that, while unique, many have to endure...and those that have counsel to offer from experience have been kind enough to do so. Support has come to us in diverse ways though, including meals, letters/cards, packages, services, words of kindness and love, DMs and comments, and prayers. Many of you have also contributed to Kim’s “last wish” and her heart’s desires: completing her documentary so her suffering would do some good in this world and show her daughter how hard she fought to stay here, continuing the outreach of her Lifted By Angels non-profit, and helping to support her beliefs and ideals through various vehicles.
. 
At this point, YOU have helped us SUCCESSFULLY REACH our monetary goal to complete her documentary. It is an overwhelming feeling to know that this has been achieved! THANK YOU! I am so excited!
.
Now, we have been informed that a couple of fundraisers are still pending or postponed out there...please know that any funds still coming in will still help with marketing, distribution, or music of her documentary Breaking into Beautiful (to include some form of Kim’s battle soundtrack requires licensing), or to support Lifted by Angels and other projects supporting @kimcankickit’s legacy. We love you and our goal is to do right by you all and Kim. This support is sacred to me and will be used in such a manner.
Please follow @stiry as they will be sharing bits and pieces of Kim’s story and submit your stories about how Kim has influenced your life at stiry.com/storieswithkim or click the link in my bio. In addition you can keep sending you DMs about your experiences with Kim as this is one way we can keep letting Kim inspire us on her kimcankickit IG page.

node.text: Kim wanted to get her story out...not for attention or fame or delusions of grandeur, but she wanted to show people what a normal person is capable of.  And although we all know she was anything but “normal”, she considered herself a normal everyday woman. I would even concede that she was much closer to “normal” before her diagnosis...but she consciously chose the “become something” path instead of the “remain the same” path. She fought tooth and nail for progress...and she surely achieved greatness through her struggles. As she looked back, it surprised her how much she had overcome. This video describes how she sought to accomplish getting her @stiry story out and why. So many of you have asked how you can help. The link in my bio will take you to her gofundme page where you can help to make her vision a reality.

This is such a beautiful example of God showing his hand in my life. He is always in the details.

When I left the hospital the last person I talked to was one of Dr. Griffin’s (lung surgeons) PA’s. He told me the staples could come out after 10 days and that we could remove them at home. Then he sent us home with a staple removal kit.

Day 10 was Saturday and I knew the staples were ready to come out. They were red and irritated. They were also causing more unnecessary pain from leaning up against them. But when I contacted Dr. Griffin he told me no. He said I had to wait the full 14 days.

By yesterday morning (Monday) all of the staples were red. They itched and were more irritated. It was very clear they were ready to come out. So I called his office again. His nurse told me I could come in Wednesday and he would take them out. Instructing me that I needed to wait for the full 14 days.

Well my very red, stubborn, I don’t like to be told what to do attitude shown through really bright last night. I handed the staple remover to my mom and told her to go for it.

Here's the thing. I have so much love and respect for my doctors. I always do my best to follow instructions and do as they ask. But this is not my first rodeo. Also, I am very in tune with my body and I knew they needed out.

I am almost six years deep into this battle and it really is the little things that help get you through. Being able to lay on my back last night without added pain from the staples was incredible. I am a little nervous to see Dr. Griffin's reaction when I see him on Wednesday but hopefully he will be understanding.

node.text:
I understand the majority of you aren’t Iowa Hawkeye fans, as you likely root for your own alma mater. However, I also understand the majority of you are Kimcankickit fans. So I wanted to present you with this opportunity. 
We don’t hold Kim up on a pedestal as an example of perfection. All that knew her can surely testify of one or more of her weaknesses. Kim accepted her flaws. If it was something she couldn’t change, she celebrated it as unique and beautiful. If it was something she could change, she would work tirelessly to improve it. She is a shining example of what a person can do and become through thought work. She disciplined and strengthened her mind which helped her keep her body healthy through necessary dietary adjustments and exercise. It helped her cope with unbelievable pain and discomfort, with a literal death sentence, with changes to her body and her mobility. Her honed mind drastically accelerated her growth as a person. She studied cancer, she studied happiness, she studied meditation, and she studied parenting. She became wise beyond her 32 years. It would be amazing to see where she would be if she’d been given another five or ten years of life. 
When I met Kim at the University of Iowa, she was already coping with a “career-ending” knee injury. But her teammates still witnessed her work ethic, her attitude, her drive and ultimately her strength. They want to remember Kim’s strength through this project. The Kim Olsen White Locker Room will be a place to help a younger generation develop that same strength. Go here to learn about the project:
https://goldrush.uiowa.edu/o/u-of-iowa/i/goldrush/s/locker-room-project

node.text:
Last Memorial Day, Kim’s sisters, Jenny and Morgan, hiked up a mountain peak near their childhood home in memory of Kim. This year, we repeated the grueling (for some of us) hike and then met at Kim’s grave to take some flowers and share a moment with her. It felt great to combine energies and thoughts around our Kimbo. It’s still unbelievable to think that she is gone. We all feel the pain of her absence in different ways, but we all feel similarly unwhole, incomplete. So we live our lives, we absorb the pain and let it pass through us. We attempt to close the vacated recesses in our hearts with differing fillers...even pretending, at times, that we are whole. Sometimes we relish our memories and think upon her life with reverence and respect. Other times we abstain speaking of her, 
avoiding the torment that follows. 
But we don’t wallow. We rise up each day and we keep fighting for happiness, peace and joy.
And although I KNOW Kim would love to know she is missed...I also know her true desire is for us to be everlastingly fulfilled and at peace. 

And for those interested, yes, we are getting a headstone for Kim’s grave. Kim’s amazingly talented father designed it and we are waiting on some rare marble to be imported. It’s hard to plan something that we want to last FOREVER. I like to do things right the first time instead of rushing through it for some imaginary deadline only to be disappointed with the outcome. 
#livelikekim

node.text:
When I start to think of how much I miss Kim, I quickly redirect that thought to Hensleigh. I lived most of my life without Kim, but Hensleigh lived her whole life WITH Kim. I cannot imagine how this little girl copes with the turmoil raging inside of her mind. I see her sadness, I feel it. I try to teach her techniques and skills to cope...mostly, how to NOT hold your emotions in. She has grown so much, right before my eyes. I see her digesting things we’ve spoken about because I’m seeing her implement them without me poking and prodding constantly. She is coming to me with her problems, and that is all I could ever hope for! But while our love continues to evolve and grow, it’s obvious that I still lack something she yearns for: female direction. I watch as she joyfully soaks up every second of attention she can get with adult females of all kinds. I am so grateful for the women in our lives that have stepped up to help ease the pain of a little girl’s broken heart. While we both understand that Kim cannot be replaced, I think we both have hopes that she can find role models to fulfill certain aspects of life that I cannot provide. 
Happy Mother’s Day to all those who fill a motherly role to anyone who needs it. And a special Happy Mother’s Day to Kimbo, Hensleigh’s Angel Mama. She left us so much to learn from.

node.text: This is the 2nd year Hens and I have had to take the wedding anniversary picture of us holding the previous year’s photo. Kim and I had done this our whole marriage, which was a fun tradition. This is number 12. I’m so grateful for my marriage to Kim. I’m so proud of who she became and the things she taught me. Today, more than anything else, I’m thankful we were able to bring Hensleigh into this world together. I’m grateful we parented her for 7 years together. If Kim gave me all of the silver in my salt and pepper hair, Hens will soon be responsible for the receding hairlines and bald spots. But rest assured, despite their effects on my hair, I’m still incredulous that I was/am blessed enough to have had these two female influences in my life.

node.text:
We celebrated an emotionally difficult day on Friday by getting some sandwiches and going on a picnic at the park. We listened to an audiobook on my phone while we ate because it helped to clear our minds. It was SO nice outside and we felt like the sun and sky almost cleansed our minds from the emotional weight of what we just experienced.

Hens and I were fortunate enough to go to the office of the @stiry crew and watch the full cut of Kim’s 90-minute documentary ( Breaking into Beautiful ) as it now stands. A couple of song licenses have been obtained, but they are still working on a couple more. The hard work and patience is paying off and we loved what we saw. 

As we watched, we felt like Kim was with us...not in a metaphorical, spiritual, or metaphysical way...but in a very real way. For an hour and a half we heard her voice speak to us and felt her physical presence near us as we witnessed past events occur in the present. I quickly realized that this is how most of you got to know her, to care about her, and to find inspiration from the way she lived. Watching her inspired me, in a new way! I can’t wait for everyone to see this, but alas, it isn’t quite complete. 

The one thing I felt the film was missing: a warning to have a box of tissues nearby and to prepare yourself for some emotional recovery time afterwards. Hens loved the show but had a good strong emotional response that I hadn’t seen for over a year from her. I think it was good for her and we spoke about it a lot afterwards. 

Spending time at the park after watching the film helped to re-ground ourselves in the present. It’s so easy to let ourselves slide into the past, to re-live the pain and trauma, to renew the anxiety and fear, and to regret actions and non-actions. It’s even easy to sometimes re-live negative or hurtful moments in order to rid my heart of the ache that exists when I really miss her, but then I begin working on removing the guilt for allowing that negativity into my heart. The emotional work doesn’t stop! 

#livelikekim #idoitforkim #doitforkim #griefrecovery #griefandloss #griefsupport #grief #kimcankickit #treaganwhite

Hi everyone! @treaganwhite here! Listen up please! 
I have NO DOUBT that the way @kimcankickit treated her body, through diet and exercise, kept her here in this world for years beyond what was predicted after her initial diagnosis. Those of you who followed her then, or have now searched her previous posts, know how she would plead with us all to take care of our bodies. Above all, she encouraged us to MOVE. Whatever that means to you, just move. Appreciate the miracle that is your body! Savor the moments when you are out of breath during vigorous exercise! Don’t take for granted the fact that you can walk around with ease, that you can ride a bike, or even that you can lift and play with your children. LOVE your body! If the time comes when you can no longer move with relative ease, you will want nothing more than to leap from your couch, bed, or chair to engage in ANY type of bodily movement. Don’t let that happen! Move your body now! Thank you Kim, for pushing us to do this. Thank you Jane ( @olsenjs ) for reminding us and carrying on with Kim’s message!  We love you both!

#kimcankickit #idoitforkim #doitforkim #movelikekim #loveyourbody #getupandmove #moveyourbody

node.text:
Nothing like a quick trip to Moab, UT as we gear up for an emotional week. Thanks @_elisecurtis and Andy for the invite!
It feels so great to visit places that Kim loved, in places that we’ve spent  lots of time with her. That’s the closest I ever feel her. There are days I still can’t feel her, and days I doubt that I ever have felt her. 
As it approaches a full year since she departed, I’m more unsure than ever about what that means for her, for us. I’m more unsure about the things that I’ve always accepted as true.
But as I focus on inviting things into my life that bring me joy, I have started to feel a peace settle upon me. As I continue to put an intentional focus on myself and Hensleigh, we both feel closer, bonded. 
We might not eat the way we used to, go to bed when we used to, or even want the same things we used to want in life, BUT we ARE taking one step after another! We are progressing. We are growing. We are experimenting. We are gaining control of our emotions. We are creating our own circle. We are forming lifelong relationships. We are deciding what we want life to be like and moving towards that. 
As Kim’s Angelversary on Valentines Day approaches, we feel bits of that dark period return. It hurts like it used to. We miss her like we used to.  Thank you all for remembering our Kim! 
If she helped you at all through this past year will you please tell us about it?! If you e moved your body because of her, tell us!
We love you all!
#kimcankickit #idoitforkim #doitforkim #angelverssary
